28":"1470–1528","1437–1528":"1437–1528","1500–1559":"1500–1559","1470–1500":"1470–1500","from 1527 to 1532":"van 1527 to 1532","1437":"1437","about 1470":"circa 1470","1500":"1500","1470":"1470","1528":"1528","1559":"1559","Melksham, Wiltshire, England":"Melksham, Wiltshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lamport, Northamptonshire, England":"Lamport, Northamptonshire, England","Naseby, Northamptonshire, England":"Naseby, Northamptonshire, England"},"en":{"about 1470–1500":"about 1470–1500","1470–1528":"1470–1528","1437–1528":"1437–1528","1500–1559":"1500–1559","1470–1500":"1470–1500","from 1527 to 1532":"from 1527 to 1532","1437":"1437","about 1470":"about 1470","1500":"1500","1470":"1470","1528":"1528","1559":"1559","Melksham, Wiltshire, England":"Melksham, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Lamport, Northamptonshire, England":"Lamport, Northamptonshire, England","Naseby, Northamptonshire, England":"Naseby, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Self","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Suffolk): from the Middle English personal name <i>Sa(h)ulf</i> (Old English <i>Sǣwulf</i>, from <i>sǣ</i> ‘sea’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’).","North German: nickname from Low German <i>self</i> ‘self’ for a self-important person."],"variants":[{"name":"Selph","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Self  ."]},{"name":"Selfe","meanings":["English: variant of   Self  ."]},{"name":"Silverstone","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Aron, Emanuel, Herschel.","English: habitational name from Silverstone (Northamptonshire), probably from the Old English personal name <i>Sigewulf</i> (genitive <i>Sigewulfes</i>) or <i>Sǣwulf</i> (genitive <i>Sǣwulfes</i>; see   Self  ) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","Americanized form (translation into English) of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Silberstein  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Self was born about 1470, in Melksham, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with Robert Yorke. She died in 1500, in Naseby, Northamptonshire, England, at the age of 31."},"et":{"about 1470–1500":"umbes 1470–1500","1470–1528":"1470–1528","1437–1528":"1437–1528","1500–1559":"1500–1559","1470–1500":"1470–1500","from 1527 to 1532":"from 1527 to 1532","1437":"1437","about 1470":"umbes 1470","1500":"1500","1470":"1470","1528":"1528","1559":"1559","Melksham, Wiltshire, England":"Melksham, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lamport, Northamptonshire, England":"Lamport, Northamptonshire, England","Naseby, Northamptonshire, England":"Naseby, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":